Estimate immune cell proportions in tumor samples

Stephanie Hickey

2024-11-07

Project Summary

Here we use single-cell RNA-seq data from primary osteosarcoma in 6 treatment-naïve dogs (Ammons et al, Commun Biol. 2024 Apr 24) as a reference data set to estimate immune cell proportions in bulk tumor samples using parallel methods MuSiC, SCDC, and DWLS.

The following cell types are included in the reference data:

  1. TAM
  2. T cell
  3. Endothelial cell
  4. Osteoblast
  5. T_cycling
  6. Hypoxic_osteoblast
  7. Cycling_OC
  8. Osteoblast_cycling
  9. B cell
  10. Neutrophil
  11. IFN-TAM
  12. CD320_OC
  13. Fibroblast
  14. T_IFN
  15. IFN-osteoblast
  16. DC
  17. NK
  18. Mature_OC
  19. Mast cell
  20. TIM

Both MuSiC and SCDC are commonly used tools that take advantage of multi-subject reference data sets by appropriately weighting genes showing cross-subject and cross-cell consistency, though they use slightly different algorithms. DWLS is a newer tool that shows improved performance compared with MuSiC and SCDC using a single-subject reference in a recent benchmarking study.

Comparison of tool performace using pseudobulk samples.

To test how well these tools work with this reference data set, I created 100 pseudobulk samples by randomly selecting 10K (of ~30K) cells from each of the listed cell types in varying proportions.I’ve compared the known proportions with the predicted proportions from each tool below.

var1 MedianCorrelation MeanCorrelation
DWLS_predicted 0.9866042 0.9844178
MuSiC_predicted 0.9165197 0.9129674
SCDC_predicted 0.6069416 0.6101138

Cell-type proportion predictions made using DWLS show the best correlation with the ground truth cell-type proportions for each sample.

Sample deconvolution using DWLS
